17 (1) In felony cases involving violations of the following:
18 (A) Code Sections 16-8-2, 16-8-14, 16-8-18, 16-9-1, 16-9-20, 16-9-31, 16-9-33,
19 16-9-37, 16-10-52, and 40-5-58;
20 (B) Article 1 of Chapter 8 of Title 16, relating to theft;
21 (C) Chapter 9 of Title 16, relating to forgery and fraudulent practices;
22 (D) Article 3 of Chapter 10 of Title 16, relating to escape and other offenses related to
23 confinement;
24 (E) Code Section 16-11-131, relating to possession of a firearm by a convicted felon
25 or first offender probationer; or
26 (F) Code Section 16-13-30, relating to the purchase, possession, manufacture,
27 distribution, or sale of controlled substances or marijuana,
28 in which defendants have either been bound over to the superior court based on a finding
29 of probable cause pursuant to a commitment hearing under Article 2 of this chapter or
30 have expressly or by operation of law waived a commitment hearing, the district attorney
31 shall have authority to prefer accusations, and the defendants shall be tried on such
32 accusations according to the same rules of substantive and procedural laws relating to
33 defendants who have been indicted by a grand jury.
34 (2) All laws relating to rights and responsibilities attendant to indicted cases shall be
35 applicable to cases brought by accusations signed by the district attorney.
36 (3) The accusation need not be supported by an affidavit except in those cases in which
37 the defendant has not been previously arrested in conjunction with the transaction
38 charged in the accusation or when the accusation is to be used as the basis for the
39 issuance of an arrest warrant.
